english:
  title: A Funerary Ode Composed on Behalf of Kwon Il-jae for His Mother
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, your bereaved son, humbly present this offering to the spirit of my departed mother, the Late Grand Lady of Yongga County.

    Alas, such is the way of all flesh—none escape death's threshold. How could any mortal claim eternal life? Those who fall in youth need not be mourned alone; even those blessed with long years often suffer prolonged illness, lying abed in torment, wishing for death yet denied even that mercy. Yet my mother, at ninety-five, knew a different fate. From her tenth year, when she came to our house as a bride, she labored in raising children for twenty-two years, and enjoyed the harmony of husband and wife for fifty years beyond. My late father, blessed with righteousness and frugality, was favored by Heaven and lived to seventy-five. When he departed suddenly, my mother was but seventy-two. From that hour, my heart wavered between fear and gratitude. Now, at seventy-four myself, I have been graced with the highest office, and wealth beyond measure—yet my mother endured, until this day.

    Alas, it was her virtue—her goodness sown like hidden seeds—that bore such abundant fruit, granting her these long years. Should she not have faced death as one returns home? What sadness could remain?

    Yet I stand alone, without siblings to share this burden. I abandoned my youth to service, my age to ambition. Thirty years I wandered far from home, counting only my own rise as filial duty, neglecting the warmth of her presence, the sweetness of her care. Now that she is gone, what can be said?

    Some came to console me, speaking of death and life as mere morning and evening, of the rarity of an aged son in mourning, of the sage's wisdom not to wound the living for the dead. But who truly comprehends that a mother's love, deepening with age, cannot but grieve at its own decay?

    Now, at this hundredth day, I make offerings at Yongcheon Temple, performing rites of remembrance and prayer. With reverent heart and humble gifts of tea and fruit, I present this tribute to your spirit.

    Alas, receive this offering.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yongga County: The title given to the mother in her later years'
  - key: ''
    value: '琴瑟 (harmony of lute and zither): A classical metaphor for marital harmony'
  - key: ''
    value: '陰德 (hidden virtue): Accumulated merit and goodness not made public'
  - key: ''
    value: '養志 (nourish one''s will): To fulfill one''s ambitions and aspirations'
  - key: ''
    value: '溫情甘旨 (warmth and delicacies): The comfort of parental presence and care'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hundredth day: The traditional memorial service held one hundred days after death'
